                <head>Ode to William H. Seward</head>
                <origin>Morning Pennsylvanian</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Political poem decrying John Brown and "Black Republicans," calls for
                    Seward's steady hand at the helm of the ship of state.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look>x</look>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>04</column>
                <head>Negro Life and Troubles in Canada</head>
                <origin>New York Herald</origin>
                <commentary/>
                <excerpt>"Why didn't they mind their own business and leave the niggers where they
                    would have been well fed and comfortably clothed, in the cabins of their
                    Southern masters?"</excerpt>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Summarizes account in Herald which investigated living conditions among
                    blacks in Canada and found them poor. Editor points out that this is their own
                    fault for aiding runaway slaves.</summary>
                <note/>
                <look/>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>05</column>
                <head>Food for Mercantile Digestion</head>
                <origin>New Orleans Bulletin</origin>
                <commentary>Reprints to demonstrate that Southerners felt betrayed by Republican
                    electoral victories after the Brown raid.</commentary>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <names/>
                <summary>Points out the economic connections between New Orleans and Pittsburgh,
                    where the Republicans won an election, and argues that Pittsburgh lives off
                    slavery just as much as New Orleans does.</summary>
                <note>Story given a column and a half.</note>
                <look>x</look>
            </div>
            <pageNote>Illegible at bottom.</pageNote>
        </page>
